{"clauses":[{"item_alias":"K1","response":"The criticism misreads the requirement. The forbidden case is not a vague category; it specifies a concrete archaeological pattern—robust, independent local grain storage or non-palatial craft production—within defined spatiotemporal bounds (the transition period in core collapse zones). This is a datable, observable pattern of material culture. The demand for a single site, stratum, and date range confuses a hypothesis-level forbidden case (which can cover a class of evidence across a region) with a single-excavation test implication. The example given (Pylos LH IIIC pithoi) is simply one instance of the broader forbidden case already stated, not a more concrete version of it."}]}